concept_explanation.intro:
Until now, your programs execute every line in order, top to bottom. Conditionals let you SKIP code or CHOOSE between paths based on a boolean expression.

The basic structure:

```java
if (condition) {
    // run this if condition is true
}
```

The condition must be a `boolean` expression (true or false). Unlike Python or JavaScript, Java doesn't have 'truthy' values. `if (5)` is a compilation error. `if (someString)` is a compilation error. Only booleans work.

This strictness prevents a class of bugs that haunt loosely-typed languages.

concept_explanation.if_else:
Add `else` to handle the false case:

```java
if (age >= 18) {
    System.out.println("You can vote");
} else {
    System.out.println("Too young to vote");
}
```

Exactly one of the two blocks runs. Never both. Never neither.

The braces `{ }` define a BLOCK. Variables declared inside a block only exist inside that block — this is called **block scope**. We'll see why this matters in exercises.

For single-statement blocks, braces are optional:

```java
if (age >= 18)
    System.out.println("Adult");
else
    System.out.println("Minor");
```

**Strong recommendation: always use braces, even for single statements.** Why? It prevents one of the most famous bugs in software history (Apple's 'goto fail' SSL vulnerability — caused by missing braces). Some teams enforce this with linters. Modern codebases use braces always.

concept_explanation.else_if_chains:
For multiple mutually-exclusive conditions, chain with `else if`:

```java
if (score >= 90) {
    System.out.println("Grade: A");
} else if (score >= 80) {
    System.out.println("Grade: B");
} else if (score >= 70) {
    System.out.println("Grade: C");
} else if (score >= 60) {
    System.out.println("Grade: D");
} else {
    System.out.println("Grade: F");
}
```

Java checks conditions TOP TO BOTTOM and STOPS at the first true one. Order matters!

If score is 95:
- `>= 90`? Yes → print 'A' → DONE. Doesn't check the rest.

If you reverse the order, it breaks:

```java
// BUG: This always prints 'F' for anyone passing!
if (score >= 60) {
    System.out.println("Grade: D");  // 95 matches this first!
}
```

Rule: For `else if` chains with ranges, go from MOST SPECIFIC to LEAST SPECIFIC (highest to lowest threshold).

concept_explanation.nested_conditions:
You can put `if` inside `if`:

```java
if (isLoggedIn) {
    if (hasAdminRole) {
        System.out.println("Show admin panel");
    } else {
        System.out.println("Show user dashboard");
    }
} else {
    System.out.println("Show login page");
}
```

Nesting works, but DEEP nesting (3+ levels) is a code smell. It's hard to read and reason about.

Often, nested conditions can be flattened with logical operators:

```java
// Nested — okay but verbose
if (isLoggedIn) {
    if (hasAdminRole) {
        showAdminPanel();
    }
}

// Flattened — cleaner
if (isLoggedIn && hasAdminRole) {
    showAdminPanel();
}
```

Use nesting when the inner logic only makes sense given the outer condition. Use AND when both must be true for the same action.

concept_explanation.ternary_operator:
Java has ONE ternary operator: `? :` for inline conditionals.

```java
String status = (age >= 18) ? "Adult" : "Minor";

// Equivalent to:
String status;
if (age >= 18) {
    status = "Adult";
} else {
    status = "Minor";
}
```

Format: `condition ? valueIfTrue : valueIfFalse`

**When to use ternary**:
- Single, simple assignment based on condition
- Short, readable expression

**When NOT to use ternary**:
- Multiple statements (use if/else)
- Complex conditions (becomes unreadable)
- Nested ternaries (`a ? b : c ? d : e` is hard to read — avoid)

Good:
```java
int absoluteValue = (x >= 0) ? x : -x;
String message = isError ? "Failed" : "Success";
```

Bad:
```java
// Nested ternary — DON'T do this
String grade = (s >= 90) ? "A" : (s >= 80) ? "B" : (s >= 70) ? "C" : "F";
// Use if/else chain instead — much more readable
```

concept_explanation.switch_statement:
When checking ONE variable against MANY specific values, `switch` is cleaner than long `else if` chains.

Classic switch (Java 7+):

```java
switch (dayOfWeek) {
    case 1:
        System.out.println("Monday");
        break;
    case 2:
        System.out.println("Tuesday");
        break;
    case 3:
        System.out.println("Wednesday");
        break;
    default:
        System.out.println("Unknown day");
        break;
}
```

**Critical**: Always include `break` at the end of each case. Without it, execution 'falls through' to the next case (a feature, but usually causes bugs).

```java
switch (x) {
    case 1:
        System.out.println("One");
        // No break — FALLS THROUGH to case 2
    case 2:
        System.out.println("Two");  // Runs for both x=1 AND x=2!
        break;
}
```

Intentional fall-through is sometimes useful (case 1, 2, 3 all do the same thing), but write comments to make it obvious.

concept_explanation.modern_switch_expression:
Java 14+ added a cleaner switch syntax — the **switch expression** with arrow syntax:

```java
String dayName = switch (dayOfWeek) {
    case 1 -> "Monday";
    case 2 -> "Tuesday";
    case 3 -> "Wednesday";
    case 4, 5 -> "Mid-week";  // Multiple values, same result
    default -> "Other";
};
```

Benefits:
- No `break` needed (no fall-through)
- Returns a value directly
- Cleaner syntax
- Multiple values per case: `case 1, 2, 3 ->`
- Exhaustiveness check (compiler warns if cases are missing)

Use classic switch only when working with old Java versions or legacy code. For modern Java (14+), prefer switch expressions.

**What switches can match**: `int`, `byte`, `short`, `char`, `String`, `enum` (and starting Java 21, patterns and types). NOT: `double`, `long`, `boolean`, objects (without patterns).

concept_explanation.if_vs_switch:
When to use which:

**Use `if/else if`**:
- Checking ranges: `score >= 90`, `bmi < 18.5`
- Different variables in different conditions
- Complex boolean expressions
- Few options (2-3)

**Use `switch`**:
- Checking ONE variable against many exact values
- Days of week, menu options, status codes, enum values
- 4+ options to compare
- All checks against same variable

Example:

```java
// if/else (good — comparing ranges)
if (temperature < 0) coldWarning();
else if (temperature < 20) cool();
else if (temperature < 30) mild();
else hot();

// switch (good — comparing exact values)
switch (httpStatusCode) {
    case 200 -> "OK";
    case 404 -> "Not Found";
    case 500 -> "Server Error";
    default -> "Unknown";
}
```

step_by_step_solution.details:
Start with the standard structure and our test income:

```java
public class TaxCalculator {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        double annualIncome = 850000;  // 8.5 lakh
        String taxBracket;
        double taxRate;
    }
}
```

Note: `taxBracket` and `taxRate` are declared but not initialized. We'll set them in the if/else chain.

We have 6 brackets (5 with tax + 1 with no tax). This is a classic else-if chain situation.

**Critical: order matters.** Check from highest threshold downward. Why?

If we wrote `if (income >= 300001)` first, that would match for ANY income above 3 lakh — including 50 lakh. We need to check the highest brackets first.

OR — and this is cleaner — check from LOWEST upward, using strict less-than:

```java
if (income <= 300000) {
    // 0% bracket
} else if (income <= 600000) {
    // 5% bracket — must be between 300001 and 600000
} else if (income <= 900000) {
    // 10% bracket
}
// etc.
```

This works because each later condition only runs if the previous one was false. Once you're past 300000, you ARE in the 5% bracket (or higher). The chain naturally narrows down.

Implement the logic:

```java
if (annualIncome <= 300000) {
    taxBracket = "Up to ₹3,00,000";
    taxRate = 0.0;
} else if (annualIncome <= 600000) {
    taxBracket = "₹3,00,001 to ₹6,00,000";
    taxRate = 5.0;
} else if (annualIncome <= 900000) {
    taxBracket = "₹6,00,001 to ₹9,00,000";
    taxRate = 10.0;
} else if (annualIncome <= 1200000) {
    taxBracket = "₹9,00,001 to ₹12,00,000";
    taxRate = 15.0;
} else if (annualIncome <= 1500000) {
    taxBracket = "₹12,00,001 to ₹15,00,000";
    taxRate = 20.0;
} else {
    taxBracket = "Above ₹15,00,000";
    taxRate = 30.0;
}
```

Notice: no condition needed on the final `else` — if you didn't fit any other bracket, you're in this one.

Print a clean tax summary:

```java
System.out.println("=========================================");
System.out.println("          TAX CALCULATION");
System.out.println("=========================================");
System.out.println("Annual Income:    ₹" + annualIncome);
System.out.println("Tax Bracket:      " + taxBracket);
System.out.println("Tax Rate:         " + taxRate + "%");
System.out.println("Estimated Tax:    ₹" + estimatedTax);
System.out.println("=========================================");
```

This works because `taxBracket` and `taxRate` are guaranteed to be set — every possible income value matches exactly one branch.

worked_example.final_code:
public class TaxCalculator {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        double annualIncome = 850000;  // 8.5 lakh
        String taxBracket;
        double taxRate;

        // Determine bracket
        if (annualIncome <= 300000) {
            taxBracket = "Up to ₹3,00,000";
            taxRate = 0.0;
        } else if (annualIncome <= 600000) {
            taxBracket = "₹3,00,001 to ₹6,00,000";
            taxRate = 5.0;
        } else if (annualIncome <= 900000) {
            taxBracket = "₹6,00,001 to ₹9,00,000";
            taxRate = 10.0;
        } else if (annualIncome <= 1200000) {
            taxBracket = "₹9,00,001 to ₹12,00,000";
            taxRate = 15.0;
        } else if (annualIncome <= 1500000) {
            taxBracket = "₹12,00,001 to ₹15,00,000";
            taxRate = 20.0;
        } else {
            taxBracket = "Above ₹15,00,000";
            taxRate = 30.0;
        }

        // Calculate tax (simplified)
        double estimatedTax = annualIncome * (taxRate / 100);

        // Display result
        System.out.println("=========================================");
        System.out.println("          TAX CALCULATION");
        System.out.println("=========================================");
        System.out.println("Annual Income:    ₹" + annualIncome);
        System.out.println("Tax Bracket:      " + taxBracket);
        System.out.println("Tax Rate:         " + taxRate + "%");
        System.out.println("Estimated Tax:    ₹" + estimatedTax);
        System.out.println("=========================================");
    }
}

